## Creating a New Folder
Right-click on (or into) an existing folder and select "New" &gt; "Create folder", or press Ctrl+Shift+n. Enter a name for the new folder.

## Copying/Moving Items
You can copy or move files or folders either via Cut/Copy/Paste (by keyboard shortcut or context menu) or via Drag/Drop. In the case of Drag/Drop, use the Ctrl and Shift modifier keys to switch between copy and move.

## Deleting Items
Trigger the Delete action for selected elements from the icon bar ![](data:image/png;base64,), from the context menu, or with the Del key.

## Renaming Items
Call the Rename action for a selected element from the icon bar ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAQCAYAAAAf8/9hAAAAGXRFWHRTb2Z0d2FyZQBBZG9iZSBJbWFnZVJlYWR5ccllPAAAAG5JREFUeNpiYBhowOjg4PCfEgNYQER/fz9ZmgsLCyEGGBgYMHhMPU6S5h3ZlhAGyAsgwFW4+T8ywMeHsUF6mdBN5i7aQhIfw4CvfT54+eiAZBcQNIBUF7Fgsw2dxucaFmL9ijchOTo6MoxgABBgAN+MUP7SvgB4AAAAAElFTkSuQmCC), from the context menu, or with the F2 key.

## Locking/Unlocking
Files and folders in an Doxee Content Repository can be locked and unlocked. A locked file can only be modified by the user who locked it. A lock can be "stolen" from another user if the executing user has the right to steal locks (typically only administrators). This allows admins to recover locked files when the locking user is no longer available.

All locking actions (Lock, Unlock, Steal Lock) are available from the context menu.

## Versioning
Files on a WebDAV server can be versioned. By default, a newly created file is not versioned. This means that the previous content is lost when the file is overwritten (just like a file on the local file system).

Versioning can be enabled on a file by selecting "Enable versioning" from the context menu. This creates the first version of the file from its current content.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

A versioned file can be in one of two states: checked-in or checked-out. A newly versioned file is always checked-in. This means that it is write-protected.

Calling the "Checkout" action from the context menu instructs the server to create a writeable working copy of the latest file version. Also, a lock is placed on the file, so that only the current user can write to it.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Once the file is checked-out, its content and its properties can be modified. When the user is satisfied with the changes, the new content can be persisted as a new file version by calling "Checkin" from the context menu.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The changes can be discarded by calling "Discard checkout" instead of "Checkin".

![](data:image/png;base64,)

All versioning related actions can be executed on folders as well. In this case, they are recursively applied to all files in the folder that are in the appropriate state for the action.

> Note

Calling "Enable versioning" on a folder will enable versioning for all files in the folder and its sub-folders. Files that are created or copied into the folder after the action, however, are not affected. They will still be plain, non-versioned files.

## Manage User Access Rights
Doxee Content Repository allows to manage permissions for users and groups on files and folders. These can be configured via Resource Explorer. In order to do so, open the properties dialog of an item (e.g. by right *click &gt; Properties*) and go to the tab *Security*. Once you have added users or groups here you are able to assign permissions. Note that the list of available permissions depends on the configuration of the repository in use. Please refer to the Content Repository documentation for further information on permissions.

## ZIP Import/Export
Files and folders from the repository can be exported into a ZIP file. The exported ZIP file can be imported to a different server, or to a different folder on the same server. It is also possible to stream an exported ZIP directly to the target server for import, without saving it first.

The ZIP Import/Export dialog can be opened by selecting either "ZIP Import" or "ZIP Export" from the context menu or the icon bar.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Either action will open the same dialog. "ZIP Import" will pre-fill the target directory with the selected directory, while "ZIP Export" will pre-fill the source.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In the dialog, select a source for the operation (either a ZIP file or a folder from a repository) and a target (a ZIP file, or a folder from a repository, or both). If you select a repository folder as source or target, you will see some or all of these options (based on the modules that are installed on the server, and on the data that are available from the source):

- *access control lists* (Import/Export): Includes the ACLs of the exported ZIP / imports them from the ZIP to the repository.

- *checked-out content* (Export): For versioned files that are currently checked out, export the content of the working copy instead of the last checked-in version.

- *version history* (Import/Export): Includes the version history of files into the exported ZIP / imports files from the ZIP including their versioning status and older versions.

- *auto-generated content* (Import/Export): Includes all virtual (automatically generated) resources into the exported ZIP / imports also virtual resources (they are skipped during import otherwise).

### Filtering on Import/Export
If you select a repository folder as source or target, you can apply filtering to the process. During export, this will limit the resources that are written to the exported ZIP. During import, this will limit the resources that are imported from the ZIP to the repository.

For details about filtering, please refer to [Search and filter](/doxee-platform/docs/resource-explorer-6-6-search-and-filter-1).

Note: Any filter that you specify will be applied to all resources, files and directories alike. Since most file properties that you may want to filter for are typically not set on a directory, this will exclude all directories (and therefor their contents) from the operation. In order to keep directories unaffected from the filter, add the following OR-clause to your filter: *{DAV:}iscollection=1*

### Scheduling an Import
If the target is a repository folder and the server supports it, you have the option to schedule the import for a later date:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Click the "..." right beside "Import at ..." and select a date and a time. After clicking "OK" on the dialog, the ZIP will be transferred to the server and stored there to be processed at the specified time. Scheduled imports are listed in the Import Management dialog (see [Import management](/doxee-platform/docs/resource-explorer-6-6-actions-1#import-management)) and can be cancelled from there.

### Deployment
If either server supports it, the deployment mode option will be displayed. When activated, deployment options will be displayed, and the operation will run in deployment mode.

You can edit the deployment settings by right-clicking on the .system folder and selecting "Edit deployment settings".

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Please refer to the Content Repository User Guide for more details on the deployment mode.

### Import Management
On a server that supports ZIP Import, the "Manage Imports" icon will be active:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Clicking this icon will open the Imports dialog, where you can review and manage the stored imports on that server. Actions on the individual imports are available from the context menu.
